ill.\n    32\t4. Do not manually hunt through `.git/entire-sessions/` or raw transcript files unless\n    33\t   `entire explain --commit` explicitly fails to provide the transcript.\n    34\t5. If the user provides a snippet, resolve it to exact line numbers before explaining anything.\n    35\t6. If multiple blame blocks match, include all distinct commit/checkpoint pairs.\n    36\t7. If a matching block has no Entire checkpoint, say that explicitly and give commit-level\n    37\t   context only. Do not imply a transcript exists.\n    38\t8. Keep the final explanation concise and block-focused. Do not summarize unrelated parts\n    39\t   of the file.\n    40\t\n    41\t## Workflow\n    42\t\n    43\t### 1. Resolve the target block\n    44\t\n    45\tIf the user gave `path:start-end`, use that range directly.\n    46\t\n    47\tIf the user gave a path and a snippet:\n    48\t\n    49\t- Read the file contents.\n    50\t- Find the exact snippet in the file.\n    51\t- Convert the match to `start-end` line numbers.\n    52\t- If whitespace differs but the code is otherwise identical, normalize leading indentation and\n    53\t  trailing whitespace before deciding the snippet does not match.\n    54\t- If the snippet appears multiple times, report the ambiguity and list the candidate ranges\n    55\t  instead of picking one silently.\n    56\t- If the snippet cannot be found exactly, say so plainly and stop rather than inferring a nearby match.\n    57\t\n    58\t### 2. Gather provenance\n    59\t\n    60\tRun:\n    61\t\n    62\t```bash\n    63\tgit blame --porcelain -L <start>,<end> -- <path>\n    64\t```\n    65\t\n    66\tUse the output to identify every blame block inside the target range. Group adjacent\n    67\ttarget lines that resolve to the same commit when they form one contiguous matched block.\n    68\tFor each matching block, collect:\n    69\t\n    70\t- line range\n    71\t- matched code snippet from the current file for that exact range\n    72\t- commit hash\n    73\t- author/summary when helpful for commit-only context\n    74\t\n    75\tDeduplicate identical commit/checkpoint pairs while preserving distinct ranges.\n    76\t\n    77\tAfter resolving the matching ranges, read the file contents for each matched block and keep\n    78\tthe exact snippet so the final answer can show users which code each provenance entry refers to.\n    79\t\n    80\t### 3. Explain each matching block\n    81\t\n    82\tFor each distinct matched block, run:\n    83\t\n    84\t```bash\n    85\tentire explain --commit <commit-sha> --no-pager\n    86\t```\n    87\t\n    88\tUse the output to answer:\n    89\t\n    90\t- what the agent was trying to do\n    91\t- why this block changed\n    92\t- any constraint, bug, edge case, or refactor pressure that caused the final code\n    93\t\n    94\tIf the commit view reveals a checkpoint ID and the commit-level view is not enough, fall back to:\n    95\t\n    96\t```bash\n    97\tentire explain --checkpoint <checkpoint-id> --full --no-pager\n    98\t```\n    99\t\n   100\tIf `--full` fails, fall back to:\n   101\t\n   102\t```bash\n   103\tentire explain --checkpoint <checkpoint-id> --raw-transcript --no-pager\n   104\t```\n   105\t\n   106\tIf there is no checkpoint ID, use the commit view and the code block itself to provide the\n   107\tbest available explanation, clearly marked as commit-only context.\n   108\t\n   109\t## Response format\n   110\t\n   111\tStart with a short provenance summary:\n   112\t\n   113\t```text\n   114\tWat:\n   115\t\n   116\tMatches\n   117\t- <path>:<start>-<end> -> commit <sha> | checkpoint <id>\n   118\t  ```<language>\n   119\t  <matched code snippet>\n   120\t  ```\n   121\t- <path>:<start>-<end> -> commit <sha> | no Entire checkpoint\n   122\t  ```<language>\n   123\t  <matched code snippet>\n   124\t  ```\n   125\t```\n   126\t\n   127\tThen give one short section per distinct matching block:\n   128\t\n   129\t```text\n   130\tWhy\n   131\t- <path>:<start>-<end>: <2-4 sentence explanation of why this block changed last time>\n   132\t```\n   133\t\n   134\tSnippet guidance:\n   135\t\n   136\t- Prefer the exact matched lines from the file.\n   137\t- Keep snippets tight to the matched block; avoid unrelated surrounding code unless needed for readability.\n   138\t- If the block is long, include the smallest contiguous excerpt that still lets the user recognize it and say that it was truncated.\n   139\t\n   140\tWhen the input was a pasted snippet, include the resolved line range in the answer.\n   141\t\n   142\tIf the snippet matched multiple ranges and the user has not disambiguated them, do not continue\n   143\tto transcript summarization. Present the candidate ranges and ask which one they want explained.\n   144\t\n   145\t## Trigger phrases\n   146\t\n   147\tThis skill should trigger for questions like:\n   148\t\n   149\t- \"wtf is going on with this code\"\n   150\t- \"why is this code like this\"\n   151\t- \"why was this changed\"\n   152\t- \"why does this exist\"\n   153\t- \"help me understand this block\"\n   154\t- \"what changed here and why\"\n   155\t\n   156\tEspecially trigger when the user includes:\n   157\t\n   158\t- a file range like `cmd/entire/cli/explain.go:103-107`\n   159\t- a file path plus a pasted code snippet\n","exit_code":0,"duration":{"secs":0,"nanos":2500},"formatted_output":"","status":"completed"}}
