ns info`, `entire explain --session`, `git log`, `git status`, `git branch`, `ps aux`, or any other exploratory commands. They waste time and don't give you the transcript.\n    22\t3. **Do NOT say** \"Would you like me to continue?\" or \"Let me know if you want me to pick this up.\" Just read the transcript and start working. (Exception: if the previous agent asked the user a question that was never answered, you MUST ask the user that question before proceeding.)\n    23\t4. **Do NOT summarize the session as having \"0 turns\" or \"no progress\"** without first reading the actual transcript file. The `entire` CLI metadata often undercounts — the transcript is the source of truth.\n    24\t5. **Skip your own session.** Your agent (e.g. Claude Code) also has a session in `.git/entire-sessions/`. Exclude any session whose `agent_type` matches your own agent type from the results.\n    25\t\n    26\t## Flow: Active / current session handoff\n    27\t\n    28\tWhen the user says \"current\", \"active\", or just \"hand off this session\":\n    29\t\n    30\t### Step 1: Run `entire status`\n    31\t\n    32\t```\n    33\tentire status\n    34\t```\n    35\t\n    36\tThis returns the active session ID. If the user mentioned an agent name (e.g. \"codex\"), look for that agent's session in the output.\n    37\t\n    38\t### Step 2: Find the transcript path\n    39\t\n    40\tRead the session file at `.git/entire-sessions/<session-id>.json` using the Read tool:\n    41\t\n    42\t```\n    43\tRead: .git/entire-sessions/<session-id>.json\n    44\t```\n    45\t\n    46\tThe file looks like this:\n    47\t```json\n    48\t{\n    49\t  \"session_id\": \"019d730f-e099-7910-a946-b5b20e2cfafc\",\n    50\t  \"agent_type\": \"Codex\",\n    51\t  \"phase\": \"active\",\n    52\t  \"started_at\": \"2026-04-09T09:25:21.725231-07:00\",\n    53\t  \"last_interaction_time\": \"2026-04-09T09:25:21.725657-07:00\",\n    54\t  \"transcript_path\": \"/Users/alisha/.codex/sessions/2026/04/09/rollout-....jsonl\",\n    55\t  \"last_prompt\": \"create solitaire game\"\n    56\t}\n    57\t```\n    58\t\n    59\tExtract the `transcript_path` field. This is the path to the full conversation transcript.\n    60\t\n    61\t**Fallback:** If `entire status` doesn't give you a session ID, or the session JSON doesn't exist, use the Glob tool to find all `.git/entire-sessions/*.json` files, read them, and pick the most recent one (by `last_interaction_time` or `started_at`). Filter by agent name if the user specified one. Always exclude sessions matching your own agent type.\n    62\t\n    63\t### Step 3: Extract and summarize the transcript\n    64\t\n    65\t**Phase A — Extract raw transcript** (do NOT show this to the user):\n    66\t\n    67\t```bash\n    68\tgrep -E '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' <transcript_path> | cut -c1-2000\n    69\t```\n    70\t\n    71\tIf the output exceeds ~500 lines, read the **last 100 lines** (final state) and **first 20 lines** (original task):\n    72\t\n    73\t```bash\n    74\tgrep -E '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' <transcript_path> | tail -100 | cut -c1-2000\n    75\tgrep -E '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' <transcript_path> | head -20 | cut -c1-2000\n    76\t```\n    77\t\n    78\t**Phase B — Produce a compaction summary.** Internally process the extracted transcript and produce a structured summary with these sections:\n    79\t\n    80\t1. **Task Overview** — The user's core request, success criteria, and any stated constraints or clarifications.\n    81\t2. **Current State** — Completed work: files created/modified, key decisions made, artifacts produced.\n    82\t3. **Important Discoveries** — Technical constraints uncovered, rationale behind decisions, errors hit and their resolutions, failed approaches and why they failed.\n    83\t4. **Next Steps** — Specific remaining actions, blockers, and priority ordering.\n    84\t5. **Context to Preserve** — User pre