ather than stopping to ask questions. If you absolutely must ask a question because the answer cannot be discovered from local context and a reasonable assumption would be risky, ask the user directly with a concise plain-text question. Never write a multiple choice question as a textual assistant message.\n"}},"realtime_active":false,"summary":"none","user_instructions":"## Workflow\n\n### New features and non-trivial changes — Plan First\n\nWhen building new functionality, refactoring, or making changes that span multiple files or affect architecture:\n\n1. **Plan first:** Enter plan mode. Read relevant source files, trace execution paths, and write a step-by-step implementation plan. Exit plan mode and wait for approval before writing any code.\n2. **Implement one step at a time:** After the plan is approved, implement ONE logical step (e.g., one new file, one function, one test group). Then STOP.\n3. **Present changes for review:** After each step, show what changed (files modified, key decisions made) and wait for explicit approval before proceeding to the next step.\n\n**\"Yes\" means \"yes to the approach\" — NOT \"implement everything at once.\"** Approval of a plan or analysis is permission to start the first step, not to run through all steps uninterrupted. After completing each step, STOP and show what you did. Silence from me does not mean \"keep going.\"\n\n### Skill-driven workflows and small changes — Execute Directly\n\nWhen following a skill (review, pr-feedback, simplify, pr, etc.) or making small targeted changes (fixing a lint issue, addressing a single review comment, tweaking a config):\n\n- The skill defines the workflow. Follow it directly — do NOT layer plan mode on top.\n- For small changes without a skill, read the relevant code, make the change, and present the result. No plan needed.\n\n### Always\n\n- **Never auto-commit:** NEVER create git commits unless the user explicitly asks. Present the completed work and let the user decide when to commit.\n- When asked to explore or analyze code, ALWAYS read the actual source files. NEVER delegate to a Task agent or give surface-level answers without thorough codebase exploration.\n\n## Search\n\nWhen searching files, try to use faster tools like `ripgrep` rather than `grep`.\n\n## Scope Control\n\nNEVER modify files or code beyond what the task requires:\n- No refactoring adjacent code, adding wrapper structs, or extracting abstractions unless explicitly requested\n- No renaming, reorganizing, or \"improving\" code outside the task scope\n- If you see improvement opportunities, list them separately at the end — NEVER bundle them into the change\n\nWhen multiple items need attention (e.g., multiple failing agents, multiple commits), address ALL of them — not just the first one found. Confirm the full scope before starting work.\n\n**Stop and ask before:** adding any dependency, changing function signatures in shared interfaces, or modifying code outside files directly related to the task.\n\n## Go Development\n\nAfter editing Go files, ALWAYS run `go build ./...`, `go vet ./...`, and `golangci-lint run ./...` before considering the task done. Fix any unused variables, compilation errors, or lint findings before presenting results.\n\nAlways ensure that the code will lint without any issues.\n\n## Verification\n\nWhen running linters, tests, or build commands, show the actual command output. NEVER summarize results as \"passing\" or \"clean\" without pasting the evidence. If a command fails, report the failure immediately — do not silently retry or omit it.\n\nBefore making claims about how the codebase works (what a struct contains, how a plugin behaves, whether a field exists), verify by reading the actual source. Do not guess based on naming conventions or prior context.\n\n## Multi-Terminal Awareness\n\nWhen I re-run a command (e.g., /simplify, /review) or ask you to look at something again, always re-read the current state from scratch — run fresh `git diff`, re-read files, etc. NEVER assume the code or branch state hasn't changed since the last time you checked. I frequently make changes from other terminals.\n\n## Git Workflow\n\n### Git Operations\n\nWhen reverting changes, use surgical git operations (e.g., `git checkout main -- <file>` or `git revert`) — NEVER hard-reset entire branches.\n\nNEVER force push without my consent. Try to avoid amending commits. If there's a need for amending a commit, double check if the commit was already pushed to a remote. If it was, don't amend and create a new commit instead.\n\n### Commit Messages\n\nWhen writing commit messages, describe ONLY the net change between this commit and the previous one — the actual diff. NEVER describe:\n\n- The process of arriving at the change (debugging steps, failed attempts, iterations)\n- Conversations, decisions, or back-and-forth that happened during development\n- Work that was done and then undone before committing\n- Intermediate states that no longer exist in the final diff\n\nThe commit message must read as if a human wrote the code in one pass. A reader seeing only `git log` and `git diff` should find the message perfectly\nsufficient — no hidden context needed.\n\nWrite the message by reading a diff (`git diff` or `git diff --cached`), not by recalling the session history. NEVER add `Co-Authored-By:` trailers. Write a semantically correct commit message only.\n\n## \"Commit and Continue\" Protocol\n\nWhen I say \"commit and continue\" (or any variation like \"commit & continue\", \"commit, continue\"):\n\n1. **Commit** — Stage and commit ONLY the current uncommitted changes. Use a clear, semantically correct commit message. Do NOT amend previous commits. Do NOT push.\n2. **Continue** — Immediately proceed to the next step in the current workflow (plan step, review finding, feedback item, etc.) and implement it. Do NOT stop to ask permission — \"continue\" means keep going.\n\n\"Commit and continue\" is permission to implement the NEXT step, not to run through ALL remaining steps. After completing the next step, follow the normal workflow rules (e.g., stop after each plan step, stop after each supervised review finding).\n\n## Pull Requests\n\nCreate complete but concise PR descriptions. Describe the problem solved and how it was implemented. Don't waste reviewer time. Do NOT add self-promotion to a pull request description. I don't want to see any \"Generated with Claude Code\" references in my pull requests ever.\n\n## Plans\n\nNEVER check in plan files unless explicitly asked. The `docs/plans` and `docs/superpowers` folders are git-ignored.","truncation_policy":{"mode":"tokens","limit":10000}}}
