ppet>\n   235\t  ```\n   236\t- <path>:<start>-<end> -> untracked file | no committed history\n   237\t  ```<language>\n   238\t  <matched code snippet>\n   239\t  ```\n   240\t````\n   241\t\n   242\tFor checkpoint-backed ranges, give one short section per distinct matching block:\n   243\t\n   244\t```text\n   245\tWhy\n   246\t- <path>:<start>-<end>: <2-4 sentence explanation of why this block changed last time>\n   247\t```\n   248\t\n   249\tFor ranges without checkpoint-backed context, use this separate section instead:\n   250\t\n   251\t```text\n   252\tCurrent-code fallback (not checkpoint-backed)\n   253\t- <path>:<start>-<end>: <2-4 sentence explanation of what the current code does, plus any\n   254\t  limits on what can be inferred without checkpoint history>\n   255\t```\n   256\t\n   257\tSnippet guidance:\n   258\t\n   259\t- Prefer the exact matched lines from the file.\n   260\t- Keep snippets tight to the matched block; avoid unrelated surrounding code unless needed for readability.\n   261\t- If the block is long, include the smallest contiguous excerpt that still lets the user recognize it and say that it was truncated.\n   262\t\n   263\tWhen the input was a pasted snippet, include the resolved line range in the answer.\n   264\t\n   265\tIf the snippet matched multiple ranges and the user has not disambiguated them, do not continue\n   266\tto transcript summarization. Present the candidate ranges and ask which one they want explained.\n   267\t\n   268\t## Trigger phrases\n   269\t\n   270\tThis skill should trigger for questions like:\n   271\t\n   272\t- \"wtf is going on with this code\"\n   273\t- \"what happened here\"\n   274\t- \"what happened to this block\"\n   275\t- \"why is this code like this\"\n   276\t- \"why was this changed\"\n   277\t- \"why does this exist\"\n   278\t- \"help me understand this block\"\n   279\t- \"what changed here and why\"\n   280\t\n   281\tEspecially trigger when the user includes:\n   282\t\n   283\t-