 diff`, re-read files, etc. NEVER assume the code or branch state hasn't changed since the last time you checked. I frequently make changes from other terminals.\n\n## Git Workflow\n\n### Git Operations\n\nWhen reverting changes, use surgical git operations (e.g., `git checkout main -- <file>` or `git revert`) — NEVER hard-reset entire branches.\n\nNEVER force push without my consent. Try to avoid amending commits. If there's a need for amending a commit, double check if the commit was already pushed to a remote. If it was, don't amend and create a new commit instead.\n\n### Commit Messages\n\nWhen writing commit messages, describe ONLY the net change between this commit and the previous one — the actual diff. NEVER describe:\n\n- The process of arriving at the change (debugging steps, failed attempts, iterations)\n- Conversations, decisions, or back-and-forth that happened during development\n- Work that was done and then undone before committing\n- Intermediate states that no longer exist in the final diff\n\nThe commit message must read as if a human wrote the code in one pass. A reader seeing only `git log` and `git diff` should find the message perfectly\nsufficient — no hidden context needed.\n\nWrite the message by reading a diff (`git diff` or `git diff --cached`), not by recalling the session history. NEVER add `Co-Authored-By:` trailers. Write a semantically correct commit message only.\n\n## \"Commit and Continue\" Protocol\n\nWhen I say \"commit and continue\" (or any variation like \"commit & continue\", \"commit, continue\"):\n\n1. **Commit** — Stage and commit ONLY the current uncommitted changes. Use a clear, semantically correct commit message. Do NOT amend previous commits. Do NOT push.\n2. **Continue** — Immediately proceed to the next step in the current workflow (plan step, review finding, feedback item, etc.) and implement it. Do NOT stop to ask permission — \"continue\" means keep going.\n\n\"Commit and continue\" is permission to implement the NEXT step, not to run through ALL remaining steps. After completing the next step, follow the normal workflow rules (e.g., stop after each plan step, stop after each supervised review finding).\n\n## Pull Requests\n\nCreate complete but concise PR descriptions. Describe the problem solved and how it was implemented. Don't waste reviewer time. Do NOT add self-promotion to a pull request description. I don't want to see any \"Generated with Claude Code\" references in my pull requests ever.\n\n## Plans\n\nNEVER check in plan files unless explicitly asked. The `docs/plans` and `docs/superpowers` folders are git-ignored.","truncation_policy":{"mode":"tokens","limit":10000}}}
